         xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"
         xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
         xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
         xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
         xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
         xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
  <title>Choice of Flood Quantile Estimator</title>

  <para>This section considers the following question: Given data D, what is the best estimate of
    the 1 in Y AEP flood discharge.</para>

  <para>If the true value of <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> were known, then the pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>q</mi>
              <mo>|</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> can be used to compute the flood quantile <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </msub>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>. For AM series the 1 in Y AEP quantile is defined as:</para>

  <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_aq26s">
    <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mi>Q</mi>
      <mo>&#x2264;</mo>
      <msub>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mi>Y</mi>
      </msub>
      <mo>|</mo>
      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      <mo>=</mo>
      <mfrac>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mi>Y</mi>
      </mfrac>
      <mo>=</mo>
      <munderover>
        <mstyle mathsize="140%" displaystyle="true">
          <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
        </mstyle>
        <mrow>
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mi>&#x221E;</mi>
      </munderover>
      <mi>p</mi>
      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
      <mi>q</mi>
      <mo>|</mo>
      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      <mi>d</mi>
      <mi>q</mi>
    </math>
  </equation>

  <para>However, in practice the true value of <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> (as well as the distribution family) is unknown. All that is known about <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>, given the data D, is summarized by a probability distribution with pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mo>|</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>D</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>. <xref linkend="b3_ch2_s6"/> describes how this distribution may be obtained –
    this distribution is the posterior distribution if performing a Bayesian analysis or the
    sampling distribution if performing a bootstrap analysis.</para>

  <para>If the true value of <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> is not known, it follows that the true value of the quantile <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </msub>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> is not known. The uncertainty about <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> described by the pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mo>|</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>D</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation> , translates into uncertainty about the quantile, described by the quantile
    predictive pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </msub>
        <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
        <mi>D</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>. The question then arises, which value from the quantile predictive pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </msub>
        <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
        <mi>D</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>should be adopted as the flood quantile estimate? This section presents two
    approaches for determining the best estimate of a flood discharge with a 1 in Y AEP knowing the
    pdf <inlineequation>
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mo>|</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>D</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </inlineequation>.</para>

  <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_sw7yg">
    <title>Expected Parameter Quantiles</title>
    <para>In general the estimation of a design quantile should be guided by the consequences of
      under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162346+1100" content="-"?> or
      over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162350+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        <citation>b3_c2_r68</citation>. This section considers the case where the consequence of
      over- and under-design is expressed by some measure of the difference between the true and
      estimated 1 in Y AEP quantiles – this difference is called the quantile error.</para>

    <para>The loss function <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mrow>
            <mi>L</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mo>[</mo>
              <mrow>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>,</mo>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>]</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> describes the loss or consequence when the true quantile <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mrow>
            <mo>(</mo>
            <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            <mo>)</mo>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>, which depends on <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>, is incorrectly estimated by <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mrow>
            <mo>(</mo>
            <mi>D</mi>
            <mo>)</mo>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>, which depends on the data D. Because the true value of <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> is uncertain, the best estimator <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <msub>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mi>D</mi>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>o</mi>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mi>t</mi>
            </mrow>
          </msub>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> is the one that minimises the expected loss:</para>

    <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_uko3q">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </msub>
        <msub>
          <mrow>
            <mo>(</mo>
            <mi>D</mi>
            <mo>)</mo>
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            <mi>o</mi>
            <mi>p</mi>
            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>&#x2190;</mo>
        <mi>min</mi>
        <mstyle displaystyle="true">
          <mrow>
            <munder>
              <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </munder>
            <mrow>
              <mi>L</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>[</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>,</mo>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>]</mo>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mo>|</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mi>D</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
      </math>
    </equation>

    <para>The optimal quantile estimator depends on the choice of loss
    function.</para>

    <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_x9c77">
      <title>Quadratic loss</title>

      <para>The quadratic loss function may be appropriate when the consequences of
        under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162346+1100" content="-"?> or
        over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162350+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        are judged to be
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162356+1100" content="the "?>same
        and
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162358+1100" content="the "?>loss
        is proportional to the square of the quantile error. The loss function is expressed
          as:<equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_oxco0">
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>L</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mo>[</mo>
              <mrow>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>,</mo>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>]</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mo>&#x221D;</mo>
            <msup>
              <mrow>
                <mo>[</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>&#x2212;</mo>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>]</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mn>2</mn>
            </msup>
          </math>
        </equation></para>

      <para>The expected value of this loss function is
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162413+1100" content="commonly "?>referred
        to as the Mean Squared Error
        (MSE)<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162431+1100" content=". It "?><?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162433+1100"?>,
        which <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162459+1100" content="can be "?>show<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162500+1100"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162500+1100" content="n"?>
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162454+1100"?>that
        <?oxy_insert_end?>the optimal quantile estimator is the expected value of <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <msub>
              <mi>q</mi>
              <mi>Y</mi>
            </msub>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mi>D</mi>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </math>
        </inlineequation>
        <citation>b3_c2_r24</citation>:</para>

      <para><equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_s97qk">
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>E</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mo>[</mo>
              <mrow>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>|</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>]</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mo>=</mo>
            <mstyle displaystyle="true">
              <mrow>
                <munder>
                  <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                </munder>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                  <mi>p</mi>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>(</mo>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>|</mo>
                        <mi>D</mi>
                      </mrow>
                    </mrow>
                    <mo>)</mo>
                  </mrow>
                  <mi>d</mi>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
            </mstyle>
          </math>
        </equation></para>

      <para><citation>b3_c2_r69+1</citation> observes that this integral may not exist for some of
        the probability distributions used in Flood Frequency Analysis. To avoid this problem the
        following first-order approximation may be used:</para>

      <para><equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_m9gsz">
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <semantics>
              <mrow>
                <mi>E</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>[</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <msub>
                      <mi>q</mi>
                      <mi>Y</mi>
                    </msub>
                    <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>]</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>=</mo>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>[</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <mi>E</mi>
                    <mrow>
                      <mo>(</mo>
                      <mrow>
                        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                        <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                        <mi>D</mi>
                      </mrow>
                      <mo>)</mo>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>]</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
            </semantics>
          </math>
        </equation></para>

      <para>where <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>E</mi>
            <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
            <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
            <mi>D</mi>
            <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> is the expected parameter given the data D:</para>

      <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_p4y0l">
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <semantics>
            <mrow>
              <mi>E</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>[</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mo>]</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mo>=</mo>
              <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </mrow>
          </semantics>
        </math>
      </equation>

      <para>The term <inlineequation>
          <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mrow>
              <msub>
                <mi>q</mi>
                <mi>Y</mi>
              </msub>
              <mo>[E(θ|D)]</mo>
            </mrow>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> is referred to as the expected parameter 1 in Y AEP quantile. When this
        term is used it is understood that the quantile is computed with <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> assigned <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
            <mi>E</mi>
            <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
            <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
            <mi>D</mi>
            <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
            <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
          </math>
        </inlineequation>.</para>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_97ehe">
      <title>Linear asymmetric loss</title>

      <para>The linear asymmetric loss function may be appropriate when the consequences of
        under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162525+1100" content="-"?> and
        over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162529+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        are judged to be different. The loss function is expressed as:</para>

      <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_ggb3h">
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mi>L</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <mi>D</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          <msub>
            <mtext>,q</mtext>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
          <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
          <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
          <mo>=</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mo>{</mo>
            <mrow>
              <mtable columnalign="left">
                <mtr columnalign="left">
                  <mtd columnalign="left">
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mtext>(&#x03B8;</mtext>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>&#x2212;</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>D</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>if</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>&#x003E;</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>D</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>,</mo>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x00A0;underdesign</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                    </mrow>
                  </mtd>
                </mtr>
                <mtr columnalign="left">
                  <mtd columnalign="left">
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>&#x03B2;</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>D</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>&#x2212;</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>if</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>&#x2264;</mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                        <mi>Y</mi>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                      <mi>D</mi>
                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                      <mo>,</mo>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x00A0;overdesign</mtext>
                      <mtext>&#x2009;</mtext>
                    </mrow>
                  </mtd>
                </mtr>
              </mtable>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </equation>

      <para>where <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> and <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B2;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> are the loss coefficients for
        under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162536+1100" content="-"?> and
        over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162540+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        respectively. It can be shown that the quantile estimator that
        minimi<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162547+1100" content="z"?><?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162547+1100"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>es
        the expected asymmetric linear loss must satisfy
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162612+1100"?>the following<?oxy_insert_end?>
        <citation>b3_c2_r24</citation>:</para>

      <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_xmck8">
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <semantics>
            <mrow>
              <mi>P</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>Q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>&#x2264;</mo>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mi>Y</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <msub>
                    <mrow>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>(</mo>
                        <mi>D</mi>
                        <mo>)</mo>
                      </mrow>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>o</mi>
                      <mi>p</mi>
                      <mi>t</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mo>=</mo>
              <mfrac>
                <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
                  <mo>+</mo>
                  <mi>&#x03B2;</mi>
                </mrow>
              </mfrac>
            </mrow>
          </semantics>
        </math>
      </equation>

      <para>When <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> equals <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B2;</mi>
            <mo>,</mo>
            <msub>
              <mi>q</mi>
              <mi>Y</mi>
            </msub>
            <msub>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mi>D</mi>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                <mi>o</mi>
                <mi>p</mi>
                <mi>t</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
          </math>
        </inlineequation>,
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162639+1100"?>it
        <?oxy_insert_end?>is the median of the quantile predictive distribution. However, when <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mi>&#x03B1;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation> equals <inlineequation>
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <mn>4</mn>
            <mi>&#x03B2;</mi>
          </math>
        </inlineequation>,
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162645+1100"?>it implies
        <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162649+1100" content="implying "?><?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162657+1100"?>that
        <?oxy_insert_end?>the consequences of
        under<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162652+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        are four times more severe than
        over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162704+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design,
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162712+1100"?>which
        <?oxy_insert_end?>is the 80-percentile of the predictive distribution, a far more
        conservative estimate than the median.</para>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_zbwef">
    <title>Expected AEP Quantiles</title>

    <para>This section considers a different perspective on selecting a
    quantile estimator. In the previous section the uncertainty in the
    quantile for a given AEP was considered. In this section the uncertainty
    in AEP for a given q is considered.</para>

    <para><citation>b3_c2_r69+1</citation> showed that the dependence of the flood peak pdf on
      uncertain parameters can be removed using total probability to yield the design flood
      distribution:</para>

    <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_anzoc">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mo>|</mo>
              <mi>D</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mstyle displaystyle="true">
          <mrow>
            <munder>
              <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </munder>
            <mrow>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>|</mo>
                    <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>|</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
      </math>
    </equation>

    <para>This distribution only depends on the data D (and the assumed
    probability family).</para>

    <para>The design flood quantile q<subscript>Y</subscript> with X% AEP can
    be derived by solving:</para>

    <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_xze2m">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mo>&#x003E;</mo>
            <msub>
              <mi>q</mi>
              <mi>Y</mi>
            </msub>
            <mrow>
              <mo>|</mo>
              <mi>D</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mstyle displaystyle="true">
          <mrow>
            <munder>
              <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </munder>
            <mrow>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mstyle displaystyle="true">
                    <mrow>
                      <munderover>
                        <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                        <mrow>
                          <msub>
                            <mi>q</mi>
                            <mi>Y</mi>
                          </msub>
                        </mrow>
                        <mi>&#x221E;</mi>
                      </munderover>
                      <mrow>
                        <mi>p</mi>
                        <mrow>
                          <mo>(</mo>
                          <mrow>
                            <mi>q</mi>
                            <mrow>
                              <mo>|</mo>
                              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                            </mrow>
                          </mrow>
                          <mo>)</mo>
                        </mrow>
                        <mi>d</mi>
                        <mi>q</mi>
                      </mrow>
                    </mrow>
                  </mstyle>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>|</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mfrac>
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mi>Y</mi>
        </mfrac>
      </math>
    </equation>

    <para>This quantile is greater than the expected parameter X% AEP quantile
    <inlineequation>
        <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mrow>
            <msub>
              <mi>q</mi>

              <mi>Y</mi>
            </msub>

            <mo>[E(θ|D)]</mo>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>. To gain further insight suppose we make
    q<subscript>Y</subscript> equal to the expected parameter X% AEP quantile
    and compute its design flood AEP using <xref linkend="b3_ch2_e_xze2m"/>.
    Noting the inner integral is the probability of the flood peak exceeding
    <inlineequation>
        <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mrow>
            <msub>
              <mi>q</mi>

              <mi>Y</mi>
            </msub>
          </mrow>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> given a particular value of <inlineequation>
        <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mi>θ</mi>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> , <xref linkend="b3_ch2_e_xze2m"/> can be rewritten
    as:</para>

    <para><equation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mtable columnalign="left">
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mi>p</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <mi>q</mi>
                    <mo>&#x003E;</mo>
                    <msub>
                      <mi>q</mi>
                      <mi>Y</mi>
                    </msub>
                    <mrow>
                      <mo>|</mo>
                      <mi>D</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>=</mo>
                <mstyle displaystyle="true">
                  <mrow>
                    <munder>
                      <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    </munder>
                    <mrow>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>(</mo>
                        <mrow>
                          <mstyle displaystyle="true">
                            <mrow>
                              <munderover>
                                <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                                <mrow>
                                  <msub>
                                    <mi>q</mi>
                                    <mi>Y</mi>
                                  </msub>
                                </mrow>
                                <mi>&#x221E;</mi>
                              </munderover>
                              <mrow>
                                <mi>p</mi>
                                <mrow>
                                  <mo>(</mo>
                                  <mrow>
                                    <mi>q</mi>
                                    <mrow>
                                      <mo>|</mo>
                                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                                    </mrow>
                                  </mrow>
                                  <mo>)</mo>
                                </mrow>
                                <mi>d</mi>
                                <mi>q</mi>
                              </mrow>
                            </mrow>
                          </mstyle>
                        </mrow>
                        <mo>)</mo>
                      </mrow>
                      <mi>p</mi>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>(</mo>
                        <mrow>
                          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                          <mrow>
                            <mo>|</mo>
                            <mi>D</mi>
                          </mrow>
                        </mrow>
                        <mo>)</mo>
                      </mrow>
                      <mi>d</mi>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                </mstyle>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mstyle displaystyle="true">
                  <mrow>
                    <mo>=</mo>
                    <munder>
                      <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    </munder>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>p</mi>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>(</mo>
                        <mrow>
                          <mi>q</mi>
                          <mo>&#x003E;</mo>
                          <msub>
                            <mi>q</mi>
                            <mi>Y</mi>
                          </msub>
                          <mrow>
                            <mo>|</mo>
                            <mi>D</mi>
                          </mrow>
                        </mrow>
                        <mo>)</mo>
                      </mrow>
                      <mi>p</mi>
                      <mrow>
                        <mo>(</mo>
                        <mrow>
                          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                          <mrow>
                            <mo>|</mo>
                            <mi>D</mi>
                          </mrow>
                        </mrow>
                        <mo>)</mo>
                      </mrow>
                      <mi>d</mi>
                      <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                </mstyle>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
            <mtr>
              <mtd>
                <mo>=</mo>
                <mfrac>
                  <mn>1</mn>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </mfrac>
              </mtd>
            </mtr>
          </mtable>
        </math>
      </equation></para>

    <para>It thus follows that the expected parameter 1 in Y AEP quantile <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
          <mi>E</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
          <mi>D</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>. Moreover, it follows that the expected parameter 1 in Y AEP quantile <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
          <mi>E</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
          <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
          <mi>D</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> has an expected AEP given by <inlineequation>
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mi>P</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mo>&#x003E;</mo>
          <msub>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </msub>
          <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
          <mi>D</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        </math>
      </inlineequation> which exceeds <inlineequation>
        <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <mfrac bevelled="true">
            <mi>1</mi>
            <mi>Y</mi>
          </mfrac>
        </math>
      </inlineequation>.</para>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_up1rb">
    <title>Selection of Flood Quantile Estimator</title>

    <para>The choice of flood quantile estimator depends on whether the design is being carried out
      for many sites or a single site, on whether risk, actual discharge or average annual damage is
      of primary interest in design and on whether the consequences of
      under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162738+1100" content="-"?> and
      over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162742+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
      are different. The choice is somewhat subjective and may be a matter of policy. As a general
      guide, a non-exhaustive list of recommendations is given below:</para>

    <orderedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>In situations where there is indifference to the consequences of
          under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162754+1100" content="-"?>
          or
          over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162757+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design,
          either the expected parameter or expected AEP quantile can be chosen.</para>

        <para>Expected parameter quantiles may be applicable where:</para>

        <orderedlist numeration="lowerroman">
          <listitem>
            <para>Sizing of a structure for a given AEP is the primary consideration and minimizing
              quadratic loss, as expressed by <xref linkend="b3_ch2_e_oxco0"/>, is a reasonable
              criterion.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>Unbiased estimates of annual flood damages are required
                <citation>b3_c2_r25</citation>.</para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>

        <para>Expected AEP quantiles may be applicable where:</para>

        <orderedlist numeration="lowerroman">
          <listitem>
            <para>Design is required for many sites in a region, and the objective is to attain a
              desired AEP over all sites.</para>
          </listitem>

          <listitem>
            <para>Probability of exceedance is of primary importance for design at a single site
              (such as in floodplain management).</para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>
      </listitem>

      <listitem>
        <para>If there are significant differences between the consequences of
          under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162804+1100" content="-"?>
          and
          over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162808+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design,
          consideration should be given to using <xref linkend="b3_ch2_e_xmck8"/> as the flood
          quantile estimator.</para>
      </listitem>
    </orderedlist>
  </section>
</section>
